We are now enabled to discuss the numerical results on the hyperon mass spectrum. As already explained in section 4.3 the NJL model underestimates the ratio f

K

=f

ss

by about 15%

for non-strange constituent quark masses of the order m ss 400MeV. This shortcoming of the model is also expected to show up in the baryon sector. In order to demonstrate that the ratio f

K

=f

ss

rather than the absolute value for f

K

is the ingredient to which the results are sensitive

we compare calculations for two different sets of parameters. First, f

ss

= 93MeV is kept at its

empirical value and m = 407MeV is chosen such as to reproduce the experimental \Delta -nucleon mass difference (293MeV). For this set f

K

= 99:8MeV is predicted, i.e. f

K

=f

ss

= 1:07. The

second set of parameters is fixed such as to correctly give f

K

= 114MeV. Again m = 433MeV is

determined by demanding the experimental \Delta -nucleon mass difference. Then f

ss

= 104:9MeV

is increased considerably, however, the ratio f

K

=f

ss

= 1:09 remains almost unaltered. The

corresponding numerical results for the baryon mass difference are displayed in table 7.7. Obviously the change in the mass differences for the two sets of parameters is not larger than the change for the ratio f

K

=f

ss

, i.e. 2%. As expected the SU(3) symmetry breaking in

the baryon mass differences is considerable underestimated. It has been demonstrated that this effect is strongly correlated to problem of incorrectly predicting f

K

. The leading order

